da said “my decision to change my worklife balance follows a recent medical issue which was resolved and which caused me to reevaluate my priorities” precise information about the future plans of swoboda was not immediately available “step down” cree announced “that it is accelerating its chief executive officer succession planning and charles m swoboda will step down from his executive positions and as a member of the board of directors following a transition period” share price decline the change follows a decline in the share price of cree inc since october  on the job as ceo since  swoboda has served as the company’s chief executive officer since june  as president since january  as a member of the board of directors since october  and as chairman since april  he was chief operating officer of the company from  to june  and vice president for operations from  to  prior to his appointment as vice president for operations swoboda served as operations manager from  to  as general manager of the company’s former subsidiary real color displays incorporated from  to  and as led product manager from  to  he was previously employed by hewlettpackard company swoboda intends to stay on until a successor is appointed and thereafter will remain available as a consultant to the company to ensure a seamless transition of leadership responsibilities unplanned as a general rule when a top leader announces to step aside with no successor in place it’s a signal that the move was unexpected and too early signs for pushout forces it is not completely certain what forces eventually triggered chuck swoboda’s move the pushout score™ determined by exechange suggests that pushout forces may have contributed to the management change read the full story in the exechange report   the pushout score on a scale of  to  gauges the likelihood that a manager was pushed out or felt pressure to leave the positiona critical examination of the pushout score was published bystanford graduate school o